# Clean Architecture & DDD — Logic & Rationale

## Dependency Rule (Why It Matters)

**Direction:** domain ← application ← infrastructure. Dependencies point inward only.

**Rationale:** Domain contains business rules — they must not depend on DB, HTTP, or external libs. This allows testing domain logic with mocks, swapping DB/HTTP without touching business code, and keeping the core stable when infrastructure changes.

**In Go:** domain package imports only `context`, `errors`, `time`, and domain types. No `database/sql`, `net/http`, or third-party clients.

## Bounded Contexts

**What:** A bounded context is a boundary within which a model has a specific meaning. "Order" in Ordering context ≠ "Order" in Shipping context.

**Why:** Different parts of the system have different vocabularies and rules. Mixing them causes confusion and bugs.

**In code:** Separate packages: `internal/ordering/`, `internal/shipping/`. They communicate via events or ACL (Anti-Corruption Layer), not shared structs.

## Entities vs Value Objects

**Entity:** Has identity (ID). Two entities with same fields but different IDs are different. Mutable over time. Example: Order, User.

**Value Object:** No identity. Two VOs with same values are equal. Immutable. Example: Money, Address, Email.

**In Go:** Entity = struct with exported ID; methods mutate. Value Object = struct with unexported fields; constructor returns new instance; no setters.

**Why:** Entities model lifecycle; VOs model domain concepts that don't change identity.

## Repository Pattern

**What:** Abstraction over persistence. Interface says "get/save"; implementation knows SQL/Redis/etc.

**Why:** Domain and application layers don't care how data is stored. Tests use in-memory fake. Production uses Postgres. Same code.

**Interface in domain:** `type OrderRepository interface { GetByID(ctx, id) (*Order, error); Save(ctx, *Order) error }`

**Implementation in infrastructure:** `PostgresOrderRepository` implements the interface. Injected via constructor.

**One per aggregate:** Repository loads/saves whole aggregates, not individual entities within them.

## CQRS

**What:** Separate read and write models. Commands change state; queries return data.

**Why:** Read and write often have different shapes and scaling needs. Write model enforces invariants; read model can be denormalized for fast queries.

**Commands:** `CreateOrder`, `CancelOrder` — imperative, return `error`. Handler loads aggregate, calls domain method, saves.

**Queries:** `GetOrderByID`, `ListOrders` — return DTOs. May hit read-optimized store (e.g. materialized view).

**When to use:** Complex domains, read-heavy workloads, or when read/write models diverge. Overkill for simple CRUD.

## DTOs at Boundaries

**What:** Data Transfer Objects — structs for API request/response, not domain entities.

**Why:** API contract may differ from domain. Domain has `Order` with internal state; API returns `OrderResponse` with selected fields. Domain changes don't force API changes.

**Mapping:** Handler receives DTO → validates → maps to command/entity. Handler returns entity → maps to DTO → JSON.

**Never expose:** Domain entities directly in HTTP. They may have unexported fields, methods, or internal state that shouldn't leak.

## Service Layer

**What:** Orchestrates use cases. Calls repositories, domain services, external APIs. Manages transactions.

**Why:** Use case "CreateOrder" might: validate, load user, create order, save order, publish event, send notification. This coordination belongs in application layer, not domain.

**In Go:** One service per bounded context or per use case group. Services depend on repository interfaces (from domain), not implementations.
